Excellent question. Let me break down each indicator in plain English for long positions.

---

VWAP (10) - Volume Weighted Average Price (10-period)

What It Does

· Shows the average price institutions paid today, weighted by volume
· Think of it as the "fair value" line
· Large traders use VWAP to benchmark their execution

For a Long Position (Buy)

Condition Meaning Strength
Price > VWAP Institutions are paying above average price (bullish) Strong
Price < VWAP Institutions are paying below average price (bearish) Weak
VWAP sloping up Average price rising (bullish momentum) Strong
VWAP sloping down Average price falling (bearish momentum) Weak
Price crossing above VWAP Reclaiming institutional support (buy signal) Very Strong

Ideal for Long Entry

· Price above VWAP (by at least 0.5-1%)
· VWAP sloping up or flattening (not falling sharply)
· Price just crossed above VWAP (best entry)

Example from Today

· Price: $560.87
· VWAP: $557.85
· Price > VWAP by $3 = ✅ Bullish signal

---

RSI (14) - Relative Strength Index (14-period)

What It Does

· Measures momentum on a scale of 0 to 100
· Shows if price moved too far too fast

RSI Zones

Range Meaning Action for Long
0-30 Oversold (selling exhausted) Look for bounce (advanced trade)
30-50 Weak momentum Wait for improvement
50-70 Strong momentum ✅ Good for entry
70-100 Overbought (buying exhausted) Caution, avoid chasing

Direction Matters More Than Level

RSI Direction Meaning for Long
RSI rising (e.g., 28 → 45) Momentum improving (bullish)
RSI falling (e.g., 65 → 52) Momentum deteriorating (bearish)

Ideal for Long Entry (Standard Trade)

· RSI between 50-70
· RSI rising (higher low on RSI)
· RSI recently oversold then recovered (bounce trade)

Example from Today

· RSI: 28.29
· Too low for standard trade (would need recovery above 50)
· Potentially a bounce setup (was oversold, now recovering)

---

MFI (14) - Money Flow Index (14-period)

What It Does

· Like RSI but includes volume
· Shows if money is flowing INTO (buying) or OUT OF (selling) the stock
· More reliable than RSI alone

MFI Zones (Same as RSI)

Range Meaning Action for Long
0-30 Money flowing out (capitulation) Wait for reversal
30-50 Neutral to weak Watch for improvement
50-70 Money flowing in (healthy) ✅ Good for entry
70-100 Money flowing in too fast (exhaustion) Caution

Direction Matters

MFI Direction Meaning for Long
MFI rising (e.g., 35 → 55) Money flowing in (bullish)
MFI falling (e.g., 65 → 45) Money flowing out (bearish)

MFI vs RSI (Divergence)

Scenario What It Means
RSI rising, MFI falling Price up but volume not confirming (fake move)
RSI falling, MFI rising Price down but accumulation happening (bullish divergence)
Both rising Strong confirmation (✅ best for long)
Both falling Strong selling (❌ avoid long)

Example from Today

· MFI: 44.12
· Neutral zone (not confirming strong inflow or outflow)
· Lower than RSI suggests volume not fully supporting the bounce yet

